<h3>WHAT IS A MECHANICAL VENTILATOR</h3>        
  <p>A mechanical ventilator is a breathing machine that provides artificial breathing support. <br>
  The ventilator pumps air and oxygen into the lungs through a breathing tube. This breathing tube goes through the mouth into the windpipe. It is also called “life support”.
<br>The ventilator supports a patient while treatments are given for their medical problem, like TBI. <br>
<b>The ventilator itself does not cure the injury.</b>
<br><br>
<h3>WHAT IT IS TO BE ON A MECHANICAL VENTILATOR</h3>  
<p>It is uncomfortable to be on a ventilator. Patients often need medicines for pain and to help them relax while they are on it. 
<br>Patients cannot eat or drink by mouth while on a ventilator because of the tubes in their mouth. 
<br><br>Patients cannot make a sound when on a ventilator.
<br>Patients who are on a ventilator are very sick. They are usually on them for several days or weeks. 
<br>Many TBI patients cannot breathe or swallow on their own for many weeks or months. <br><b>Therefore, the doctor will ask you to make an important decision.</b>
</p>
<br>
<h3>WHAT DECISION AM I BEING ASKED TO MAKE?</h3>  
<p>Your loved one is still on a ventilator, and despite the best care from the doctors and nurses, your loved one is unable to come off the ventilator and breathe on his/her own.
<br>
At this point, there are <b>2 different treatment goals.</b>
<br>
<b>You are being asked to make a decision: which of these 2 treatment goals best aligns with your loved one’s goals, values and preferences.</b>
<br>
The treatment goal that you choose will affect what kinds of procedures and care are done for your loved one while they are in the ICU and afterwards.</p>
